BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:lpmaDbsRSevfslwmkSjp9
SUMMARY:Moomins' Sea Adventures & Tove and the Sea
DTSTAMP:20260413T050910Z
DTSTART:20260414T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Dive into the whimsical world of Moominvalley and the life of i
	ts creator\, Tove Jansson\, with *Moomins’ Sea Adventures* and *Tove and t
	he Sea*.\n\n*Moomins’ Sea Adventures* brings Moominvalley to life with ill
	ustrations and life-sized characters from the stories. In the center of th
	e exhibit is an interactive island complete with a lighthouse and rowboats
	 that invites visitors to imagine adventures of their own.\n\n*Tove and th
	e Sea* offers a more intimate counterpoint\, tracing Tove Jansson’s lifelo
	ng relationship with the Finnish archipelago through large-scale photograp
	hs and reflective texts.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/
	moomins-sea-adventures-tove-and-the-sea/18406909/2026-04-14T00\n\nFrom SEA
	today - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/moomins-sea-adventures-to
	ve-and-the-sea/18406909/2026-04-14T00
LOCATION:National Nordic Museum\, 2655 NW Market Street\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:I5-Xzq_2mw_PdvbsZaEzw
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260413T050910Z
DTSTART:20260414T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-14T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-14T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:9fURiMrnrfg1VkbFqjft0
SUMMARY:Low Vision Book Group: "West with Giraffes"
DTSTAMP:20260413T050910Z
DTSTART:20260414T183000Z
DESCRIPTION:Tuesday\, April 14\, 2026\, 11:30am - 1pm\n\nJoin our Low Visio
	n Book Club for a discussion of "West with Giraffes" by Lynda Rutledge.\n\
	nLocation Link:\n\nCentral Library\n\nRoom Location: Level 4 - Room 6\n\nR
	egistration Required: Registration is not required.\n\nDetailed Descriptio
	n:\n\nAbout the book:\, Woodrow Wilson Nickel\, age 105\, feels his life e
	bbing away. But when he learns giraffes are going extinct\, he finds himse
	lf recalling the unforgettable experience he cannot take to his grave. It'
	s 1938. The Great Depression lingers. Hitler is threatening Europe\, and w
	orld-weary Americans long for wonder. They find it in two giraffes who mir
	aculously survive a hurricane while crossing the Atlantic. What follows is
	 a twelve-day road trip in a custom truck to deliver Southern California's
	 first giraffes to the San Diego Zoo. Behind the wheel is the young Dust B
	owl rowdy Woodrow. Inspired by true events\, the tale weaves real-life fig
	ures with fictional ones\, including the world's first female zoo director
	\, a crusty old man with a past\, a young female photographer with a secre
	t\, and assorted reprobates as spotty as the giraffes. Part adventure\, pa
	rt historical saga\, and part coming-of-age love story\, West with Giraffe
	s explores what it means to be changed by the grace of animals\, the kindn
	ess of strangers\, the passing of time\, and a story told before it's too 
	late.\n\nEvent Logistics: View in catalog: "  West With Giraffes " byLynda
	Rutledge.\n\nContact Us: If you have questions about this event\,\n\nAsk U
	s\n\nor call 206-386-4636.\n\nADA Accommodations: We can provide accommoda
	tions for people with disabilities at Library events. Please\n\ncontactLEA
	P\n\nat least seven days before the event to request accommodations.\, All
	 Library programs are free and open to the public.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6am
	city.com/events/#/details/low-vision-book-group-west-with-giraffes/1857233
	1/2026-04-14T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/low-vision-book-group-wes
	t-with-giraffes/18572331/2026-04-14T00
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H30M
END:VEVENT
